{"info": {"author": "Oliver Philcox", "author_email": "ohep2@alumni.cam.ac.uk", "bugtrack_url": null, "classifiers": ["License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Operating System :: OS Independent", "Programming Language :: Python :: 2", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3"], "description": "# EffectiveHalos\nEffectiveHalos is a fast Python code providing models of the real-space matter power spectrum, based a combination of the Halo Model and Effective Field Theory, which are 1\\% accurate up to k = 1 h/Mpc. It can additionally compute accurate halo count covariances (including a model of halo exclusion), both alone and in combination with the matter power spectrum.\n\nThis is based on the work of Philcox, Spergel \\& Villaescusa-Navarro (in prep.), and full documentation is availble on [ReadTheDocs](https://EffectiveHalos.rtfd.io).\n\n## Authors\n**Main Authors**\n- Oliver Philcox (Princeton)\n\n**Collaborators**\n- David Spergel (Princeton / CCA)\n- Francisco Villaescusa-Navarro (Princeton / CCA)\n\n## Installation\n\nEffectiveHalos can be simply installed using pip:\n\n```\npip install EffectiveHalos (--user)\n```\n\nNote that you will need a [CLASS](https://github.com/lesgourg/class_public) installation, including the 'classy' Python wrapper, to run EffectiveHalos.\n\n\n## Basic Usage\n\nTo compute a matter power spectrum in EffectiveHalos, simply run the following:\n\n```python\nfrom EffectiveHalos import *\nimport numpy as np\n\n## Parameters\nz = 0. # redshift\ncs2 = 8. # effective speed of sound (should be calibrated from simulations)\nR = 1. # smoothing scale (should be calibrated from simulations)\nk = np.arange(0.01, 1., 0.005) # wavenumbers in h/Mpc\n\n## Load general classes\ncosmology = Cosmology(z, 'Planck18') # use Planck 2018 cosmology\nmass_function = MassFunction(cosmology, 'Bhattacharya') # Bhattacharya 2010 mass function\nhalo_physics = HaloPhysics(cosmology, mass_function, 'Duffy', 'NFW') # Duffy 08 concentration relation, NFW halo profiles\n\n## Load HaloModel class\nhalo_model = HaloModel(cosmology, mass_function, halo_physics, k)\n\n## Compute the power spectrum in both Effective and Standard Halo Models\npower_spectrum_EHM = halo_model.halo_model(cs2, R)\npower_spectrum_SHM = halo_model.halo_model(cs2, R, 'Linear', 0, 0, 0)\n```\n\nThis generates an estimate for the matter power spectrum in a few seconds. Let's plot this:\n\n![alt text](https://github.com/oliverphilcox/EffectiveHalos/blob/master/docs/ehm_tutorial_spec.png \"Effective Halo Model Power Spectrum\")\n\nA full tutorial can be found [here](https://effectivehalos.readthedocs.io/en/latest/Tutorial.html).\n\n\n", "description_content_type": "text/markdown", "docs_url": null, "download_url": "", "downloads": {"last_day": -1, "last_month": -1, "last_week": -1}, "home_page": "https://effectivehalos.rtfd.io", "keywords": "", "license": "", "maintainer": "", "maintainer_email": "", "name": "EffectiveHalos", "package_url": "https://pypi.org/project/EffectiveHalos/", "platform": "", "project_url": "https://pypi.org/project/EffectiveHalos/", "project_urls": {"Homepage": "https://effectivehalos.rtfd.io"}, "release_url": "https://pypi.org/project/EffectiveHalos/1.0.5/", "requires_dist": ["numpy", "scipy", "matplotlib", "mcfit", "fast-pt"], "requires_python": "", "summary": "Combining the Halo Model and Perturbation Theory: A 1% Accurate Model to k = 1 h/Mpc", "version": "1.0.5", "yanked": false, "html_description": "<div class=\"project-description\">\n            <h1>EffectiveHalos</h1>\n<p>EffectiveHalos is a fast Python code providing models of the real-space matter power spectrum, based a combination of the Halo Model and Effective Field Theory, which are 1% accurate up to k = 1 h/Mpc. It can additionally compute accurate halo count covariances (including a model of halo exclusion), both alone and in combination with the matter power spectrum.</p>\n<p>This is based on the work of Philcox, Spergel &amp; Villaescusa-Navarro (in prep.), and full documentation is availble on <a href=\"https://EffectiveHalos.rtfd.io\" rel=\"nofollow\">ReadTheDocs</a>.</p>\n<h2>Authors</h2>\n<p><strong>Main Authors</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Oliver Philcox (Princeton)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Collaborators</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>David Spergel (Princeton / CCA)</li>\n<li>Francisco Villaescusa-Navarro (Princeton / CCA)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Installation</h2>\n<p>EffectiveHalos can be simply installed using pip:</p>\n<pre><code>pip install EffectiveHalos (--user)\n</code></pre>\n<p>Note that you will need a <a href=\"https://github.com/lesgourg/class_public\" rel=\"nofollow\">CLASS</a> installation, including the 'classy' Python wrapper, to run EffectiveHalos.</p>\n<h2>Basic Usage</h2>\n<p>To compute a matter power spectrum in EffectiveHalos, simply run the following:</p>\n<pre><span class=\"kn\">from</span> <span class=\"nn\">EffectiveHalos</span> <span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"o\">*</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"nn\">numpy</span> <span class=\"k\">as</span> <span class=\"nn\">np</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">## Parameters</span>\n<span class=\"n\">z</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mf\">0.</span> <span class=\"c1\"># redshift</span>\n<span class=\"n\">cs2</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mf\">8.</span> <span class=\"c1\"># effective speed of sound (should be calibrated from simulations)</span>\n<span class=\"n\">R</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mf\">1.</span> <span class=\"c1\"># smoothing scale (should be calibrated from simulations)</span>\n<span class=\"n\">k</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">np</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">arange</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"mf\">0.01</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mf\">1.</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mf\">0.005</span><span class=\"p\">)</span> <span class=\"c1\"># wavenumbers in h/Mpc</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">## Load general classes</span>\n<span class=\"n\">cosmology</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">Cosmology</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"s1\">'Planck18'</span><span class=\"p\">)</span> <span class=\"c1\"># use Planck 2018 cosmology</span>\n<span class=\"n\">mass_function</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">MassFunction</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">cosmology</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"s1\">'Bhattacharya'</span><span class=\"p\">)</span> <span class=\"c1\"># Bhattacharya 2010 mass function</span>\n<span class=\"n\">halo_physics</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">HaloPhysics</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">cosmology</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">mass_function</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"s1\">'Duffy'</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"s1\">'NFW'</span><span class=\"p\">)</span> <span class=\"c1\"># Duffy 08 concentration relation, NFW halo profiles</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">## Load HaloModel class</span>\n<span class=\"n\">halo_model</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">HaloModel</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">cosmology</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">mass_function</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">halo_physics</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">## Compute the power spectrum in both Effective and Standard Halo Models</span>\n<span class=\"n\">power_spectrum_EHM</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">halo_model</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">halo_model</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">cs2</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"n\">power_spectrum_SHM</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">halo_model</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">halo_model</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">cs2</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"s1\">'Linear'</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</pre>\n<p>This generates an estimate for the matter power spectrum in a few seconds. Let's plot this:</p>\n<p><img alt=\"alt text\" src=\"https://warehouse-camo.ingress.cmh1.psfhosted.org/657d0a2484fe50c4878ecc9e6a71394a29377a28/68747470733a2f2f6769746875622e636f6d2f6f6c697665727068696c636f782f45666665637469766548616c6f732f626c6f622f6d61737465722f646f63732f65686d5f7475746f7269616c5f737065632e706e67\"></p>\n<p>A full tutorial can be found <a href=\"https://effectivehalos.readthedocs.io/en/latest/Tutorial.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">here</a>.</p>\n\n          </div>"}, "last_serial": 7000671, "releases": {"1.0.1": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "fa1ee09ca463f02f84a08d9b8b930d81", "sha256": "b64583f1709c4d8cfbe04f67f4fb4bf917fa547b50174af3db6b0faba362b079"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "EffectiveHalos-1.0.1-py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "fa1ee09ca463f02f84a08d9b8b930d81", "packagetype": "bdist_wheel", "python_version": "py3", "requires_python": null, "size": 29297, "upload_time": "2020-04-10T23:58:52", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2020-04-10T23:58:52.350473Z", "url": "https://files.pythonhosted.org/packages/33/a1/a83d2d9457d828b4618ea9277818f55993d5301b9547fb5c46654c7d325e/EffectiveHalos-1.0.1-py3-none-any.whl", "yanked": false}, {"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "48dd1704b75048ba8ce2732174f6a47f", "sha256": "422f20035227b8be1e7383963a105253e5bff1743dc6e661cde5bbe03c29d467"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "EffectiveHalos-1.0.1.tar.gz", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "48dd1704b75048ba8ce2732174f6a47f", "packagetype": "s